{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"47e7ce82-c593-40e7-80d2-13c0924ba1d0","content":"CLR activation logs are the wrong tool for this problem. They diagnose **runtime loading issues** (e.g., wrong .NET Framework version selected by the shim, runtime fails to load). They don't capture application-level exceptions like `NullReferenceException`.\n\n**For a NullReferenceException**, you'd want to:\n\n1. **Check the stack trace** — it tells you exactly which line has the null dereference.\n2. **Enable first-chance exception logging** — attach a debugger or use `dotnet-dump`/`dotnet-trace`.\n3. **Review application logs** — look for the full exception details in stderr or your logging framework.\n\nDo you have a **stack trace**, **crash dump**, or **source code** you'd like me to look at? That would let me pinpoint the bug.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c467170b-0840-454c-b37a-4cbb0cc452cd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking me to analyze CLR activation logs to diagnose a NullReferenceException. However, CLR activation logs are about how the CLR runtime is loaded/activated (e.g., which version of .NET Framework gets loaded by mscoree.dll), not about application-level exceptions like NullReferenceException.\n\nLet me check if there are any relevant files in the working directory first, and also note that I have a `clr-activation-debugging` skill available that's specifically for diagnosing CLR activation issues.\n\nBut wait - a NullReferenceException after startup is not a CLR activation issue. CLR activation logs deal with things like:\n\n\n- Which runtime version the shim picks\n- Whether the runtime fails to load\n- .NET 3.5 Feature-on-Demand dialogs\n- Loading both v2 and v4 into the same process\n\nA NullReferenceException is an application-level bug, not a CLR activation problem. CLR activation logs won't help diagnose it. I should clarify that these logs are the wrong diagnostic tool for this issue and point the user toward what would actually help—like a debugger, stack traces, or application event logs.","outputTokens":460},"id":"3ca8ef75-1db7-49cc-9005-8586bfe80f7c","timestamp":"2026-04-04T01:11:37.335Z","parentId":"15a5f27c-22e2-4bad-b217-91b7fccc63f2"}
